projects.name: NIGHTCARE

descriptions.homepage: A short escape room inspired thriller game developed using Unreal Engine 4 Blueprints.
descriptions.projectsPage: A short escape room inspired thriller game. This project was built using Unreal Engine 4 with blueprints. NIGHTCARE won the UNSW Computer Science and Engineering Top Project award.
descriptions.full: Winner of the University of New South Wales Computer Science and Engineering Top Projects award, NIGHTCARE is a 3D escape room inspired game. You wake up alone in a daycare, well after you were meant to be picked up. You will need to find various items and use them correctly to escape. You play as a toddler, and this perspective is leveraged to heighten the tension and thriller aspects of the experience. Everything is much bigger than you and every day objects are out of your reach. You must use logic to escape. However, you are not alone and you might find a threatening friend to assist you. This project was developed in Unreal Engine 4 using blueprints.

projects.contributions: This is one of my favourite projects that I have worked on so far and I made extensive contributions. I did the initial wireframing to plan out the space and atmosphere of the game. Following this I blocked out the levels in Unreal. I also coded the logic for escaping the game. This logic involved checking the current state of the game, the player and the door to ensure the puzzles were completed in the correct sequence. The game also contains a complex and dynamic hint system. I designed and coded this system. The hints are location based, so everytime a player passes through a location trigger box they have a different subset of hints they can receive. The hints system ensures the player gets a hint that makes sense for every possible game state. For example, the player should receive one hint when they have never picked up a puzzle item but are near it, and another hint if they have picked it up and dropped it. This was a complex system with many different branches. Besides theses major contributions I was also responsible for the ball pit physics, designed multiple interactive toys and the physics of dragging and pushing objects. Additionally I converted the 3D game to an unreleased VR demo version.

projects.name: Fruit Supply

descriptions.homepage: An application tracking the certification and conditions of organic fruit via the blockchain.
descriptions.projectsPage: Using the immutability and transparency of the blockchain we are able to track the certification and conditions of organic fruit as it moves through the supply chain.
descriptions.full: This project tracks organic fruit throughout the supply chain. A key issue with the organic fruit market is that fruit acquired from inadequate conditions is being fraudulently certified and sold as organic. Therefore, we need a way to verify the source and certification of the fruit. This is where the blockchain comes in. Due to the immutable nature of the blockchain we can support non-repudiation of both the producer and certifying authority. Furthermore, the blockchain is transparent, so any member of the blockchain can check and verify the conditions and certification of the fruit. To achieve these desired properties we have developed two main smart contracts. These are the products contract, which stores a hash of the off-chain fruit product data, and the cerfitying authority (CA) registry, which stores the blockchain address of the authorities who are able to certify the fruit as organic. We also developed an oracle to collect off chain conditions of the product, such as temperature. These contracts then all work together when someone tries to buy the fruit. If the fruit has not been certified by an approved authority in the CA registry, it cannot be sold. If the fruit's data has been tampered with off chain, its on chain and off chain hashes will no longer match, and it cannot be sold. If the required conditions, such as a maximum temperature have not been repsected, then the product cannot be sold. In this way we can trace the fruit supply chain, allow buyers to verify their purchase and limit fraud in the market.

projects.contributions: For the products contract I added functionality to update the product owner, add certification and update the status of the product. I was also responsible for setting up the oracle to collect off chain data from a third party API. In a full system, this API would be connected to real world hardware, such as thermometers, to provide information about product conditions.

descriptions.homepage: This website is designed to showcase my coding work so far. It was developed using NextJs 13
descriptions.projectsPage: This website was developed using NextJs 13. The purpose of this site is to simultaneously showcase my past projects and my frontend development skills.
descriptions.full: When I finished university I was faced with the dilemma of not being able to release much of my work completed during my studies due to IP policies. Although, I can share code during an interview, so I am more than happy to discuss past projects with you! However, I knew I needed a way to show people that I can code. The purpose of this site is to simultaneously showcase my past projects and to allow me to release even more source code while doing so. But I had no idea what I wanted my site to look like. So, I used figma to design high fidelity mockups of the websites pages. These mockups went through many iterations before reaching the final stage that you see here. When I was happy with my designs I finally began coding!

projects.name: Invoice Receive

descriptions.projectsPage: A software as a service project that involved designing and implementing an API for an invoice receiving platform. A user could log on and see all invoices they had received.
descriptions.full: As e-invoicing becomes increasingly popular in both industry and legislation, we need a streamlined way for businesses the receive their invoices. The e-invoices are often in the form of raw XML data, making it difficult for non-technically savvy stakeholders to deal with them. To address this we have designed a microservice to receive these XML invoices. We added a third party PDF invoice rendering API to our system to allow invoices to be presented in a user friendly way. Our service allows users to log on to check invoices they have received, send invoices to other users and download their invoices.

projects.contributions: I was the lead backend developer on this project. I implemented the authorisation and authentication system. I also coded the three ways we have for users to receive invoices. These are, via direct upload, being sent from another user, or being sent to our system via email. I then connected to the third party invoice rendering API. Additionally I set up a CI/CD pipeline to automatically test, merge and deploy the code. I deployed the code using AWS Elastik Beanstalk.
